Dickens presents Scrooge’s transformation in ‘A Christmas Carol’ as a complete
and positive one. In this extract from the end of the novella, Dickens presents Scrooge
as transformed from a hardened miser into a joyful man who embraces the Christmas
spirit. This transformation is shown through Dickens’s use of imagery as well as Scrooge’s
language. Elsewhere in the novella, Dickens uses revisited events and contrasting language
to make Scrooge’s transformation even more powerful for the reader.
In the extract, Dickens uses language relating to childhood to show the extent of
Scrooge’s transformation. Scrooge is no longer “morose” like he was at the beginning of
the novella, but instead is “as merry as a school-boy”. This simile shows that Scrooge’s
newfound happiness is as pure as that of a child. By referencing school, Dickens also
suggests that Scrooge has transformed into being receptive to education by the spirits and
open to changing his behaviour. Furthermore, Scrooge refers to himself as “quite a baby”,
which has connotations of rebirth and the ability to begin a new life. This implies that
Scrooge’s transformation is so complete that it can allow him to start life afresh as if he
were a child.
Scrooge’s language in the extract also demonstrates the extent of his transformation.
In Chapter One, Scrooge refers to those who enjoy Christmas as “fools”: this derogatory
term illustrates his condescending attitude towards the festive season. However, in the
extract, his attitude has changed completely. He uses exclamations such as “Whoop!” and
“A merry Christmas to everybody!”, which make his excitement clear. The transformation of
Scrooge’s speech has a powerful effect on the reader, as it emphasises the strength of his
Christmas spirit and how drastically he has changed.
